{"questionId":"9067856","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">A molecule of citric acid, C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>8</sub>O<sub>7</sub>, is shown.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><img style=\"margin-right:auto;margin-left:auto;display:block;\" src=\"__IMG__/ed4fd9807f2968831cf9c0c4b39bfc4c91f9569b.png\" width=\"215\" height=\"123\"></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">The equation for the first dissociation of citric acid in water is</span></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>8</sub>O<sub>7</sub> (aq) + H<sub>2</sub>O (l) <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\" \\rightleftharpoons \">\n  <mo stretchy=\"false\">⇌</mo>\n</math></span> C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>7</sub>O<sub>7</sub><sup>−</sup> (aq) + H<sub>3</sub>O<sup>+</sup> (aq)</span></span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">The dissociation of citric acid is an endothermic process. State the effect on the hydrogen ion concentration, [H<sup>+</sup>], and on the equilibrium constant, of increasing the temperature.</span></p>\n<p><img src=\"__IMG__/2decb02e9f2dc60f8f27cf76ba3877e1e4eebbe3.png\"></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><img src=\"__IMG__/bbc21c263a9a1ec9a5ef32a353b99b2fe37abac8.png\"></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9067856","referenceCode":"19N.2.sl.TZ0.a(iii)","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"The dissociation of citric acid is an endothermic process. State the effect on the hydrogen ion concentration, [H+], and on the equilibrium constant, of increasing the temperature.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a(iii)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Core","Core","Topic 8: Acids and bases","8.4 Strong and weak acids and bases","C